            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "The name Marco Reyes Ramirez often surprises people until they learn of his heritage. He is a second-generation Filipino-American, born and raised in Daly City, where the fog felt like a constant companion and the echoes of his parents' Tagalog-Spanish dialect filled their modest home. His father, an engineer, and his mother, a nurse, instilled in him a profound respect for structure and precision, which Marco channeled not into circuits or sutures, but into lines on a drafting table.\n\nHis passion for design led him to Cal Poly San Luis Obispo for his undergraduate degree in Architecture, followed by a Master's at UC Berkeley. It was there, amidst the Bay Area\u2019s cauldron of innovation, that he found his calling: sustainable architecture for the scientific community. He began his career at a large firm, diligently working his way up from a junior designer to a respected project manager.\n\nA key turning point came a decade ago when he led the design for a LEED Platinum-certified biotech research campus in Mission Bay. The project\u2019s success, coupled with its focus on community integration, solidified his reputation and led to his current role as Design Director. His work is now a high-stakes balance of managing creative teams, placating demanding tech clients, and championing environmental integrity.\n\nMarco lives with his wife, Elena, an urban planner he met during a city design review. They share a restored Edwardian flat in the Mission District. Their life is a comfortable rhythm of shared ambitions and quiet routines. His 3.5-mile commute on the J Church MUNI line is a daily ritual of observation, a time to sketch in his Moleskine notebook as the city slides by.\n\nThough successful, Marco yearns for a legacy beyond corporate campuses. He dreams of designing a public building\u2014a library or a community arts center\u2014that gives back to the city that shaped him. He aspires to mentor young Filipino-American architects, helping them navigate a field where their faces are still too few. For Marco, San Francisco is not just a backdrop for his career; it is the canvas, the client, and the unceasing source of his inspiration."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was seven, sitting at the kitchen table in Daly City. His father, the engineer, wasn't showing him a blueprint, but a *balisong*, a butterfly knife. Not as a weapon, but as a marvel of design. His father\u2019s fingers traced the interlocking steel handles, explaining the logic of the pivots, the perfect economy of its fold. In that moment, Marco felt a profound awe for its precise geometry. It was the first time he understood that structure could be an art form, a lesson that would guide his hand for the rest of his life.\n\n2.\nTwelve years ago, presenting a preliminary design to the city review board, his confidence wavered under the critique of an urban planner\u2014Elena. She cut through the jargon with a sharp, insightful question about public access and pedestrian flow. It wasn\u2019t an attack, but an invitation to make the project better, more human. In her discerning eyes, he saw a shared passion for a city built for people, not just for accolades. That challenge taught him that the best collaboration, in work and in life, is born from mutual respect.\n\n3.\nA decade ago, he stood alone on the unfinished fifth floor of the Mission Bay campus just before dawn. The steel skeleton around him smelled of cold metal and the bay's fog. Below, the city was a quiet grid of waking lights. He didn't feel the pride of a designer, but a deep, humbling responsibility. He realized then that a building wasn't just a structure; it was a promise made to its community and its environment. That quiet moment became his professional and ethical compass.\n\n4.\nLast spring, rattling along on the J Church, he watched a young man, who reminded him of his cousins, sketching the Victorians of Dolores Park into a notebook. The boy\u2019s intense focus, his quiet act of creation amidst the MUNI\u2019s lurch and rumble, struck a deep chord. Marco saw his own reflection, and felt a sudden, urgent need to build a bridge for that kid\u2014to design institutions where a new generation\u2019s talent could find a home. That moment crystallized his vague yearning for a legacy into a concrete mission.\n\n5.\nHe remembers the day their offer was accepted on the Edwardian flat in the Mission. As he and Elena stood in the empty living room, sunlight streamed through the bay windows, illuminating dust motes dancing in the air. He ran his hand over the original, intricate molding of the fireplace. It was weathered, imperfect, but held a century of stories. In that touch, he felt a profound connection to San Francisco\u2014not as an architect changing its skyline, but as a resident, becoming part of its history."
